<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-161-360  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 161 360.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  Feb 21 1990 pB1(W) pB1(E) 18 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Direct-broadcast TV may be getting off the ground. (direct-to-homesatellite) (Media)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Landro, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Direct-to-home satellite TV is closer to reality.andP;  Severalcompanies plan ventures: Hughes Communications announces a venturewith Rupert Murdoch's News Corp, envisioning a direct broadcastservice (DBS) in the US; General Electric's National BroadcastingCompany and Cablevision Systems, which already have a cableprogramming partnership, may join with Hughes and News Corp; andGeneral Electric's GE American Communications unit will join withnine cable operators to form a joint venture called K PrimePartners.andP;  Initially, a market of 20 million TV households notcurrently served by cable is at issue; later, DBS systems mightcompete directly with cable.andP;  The FCC is encouraging competitionfrom alternative program delivery services, so DBS looksattractive to investors.andP;  Moreover, the cable industry facespossible regulatory restrictions imposed by Congress.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hughes Communications Inc. (contracts)News Corporation Ltd. (contracts)National Broadcasting Company Inc. (contracts)Cablevision Systems Corp. (contracts)GE American Communications Inc. (joint ventures).andO;Topic:     Direct Satellite CommunicationsTelevisionOutlookIndustry AnalysisCooperative AgreementCable TVUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionGovernment RegulationUnited States. CongressTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>